<br>
Now there's imbued, but there's little in the way of imbued that matters.  It still would be nice to be able to convert or go apostate and become agnostic.  I wouldn't put any restrictions on it, though.  I like unique characters and the racial restrictions make characters more stereotyped.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A Paladin knight in shining armor spots me (a Discordant Evil necromancer) from a distance of 100 yards. Without even bothering to study my clothes or my equipment, there should be a good chance that the Paladin would greatly detect a strong evil aura emanating from my presence. <br>
<br>
Doesn't this make sense in terms of role playing? I think it makes a lot of sense!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Actually, alignments are IMHO, one of the least RP'ish things here.  They're very D&amp;D, but not very RP; eg. a level one inky that had done nothing more evil than slay a few spiderlings would be sensed as evil.  Uh, yeah, that makes sense.  A level 60 SK that had slain your races guards repeatedly -- now that character might radiate evil.  Tying /con to your game actions would be nicer than tying it to racial stereotypes. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvallshadowstrife.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vall Shadowstrife</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/27/02 7:22:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1206.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmmm</span><hr size=1> As a whole, I don't believe in alignment. I despise it, and the very idea of it.<br>
<br>
People, characters included, don't just stick to one course of action. Maybe it's me, but my actions vary from downright nasty to being the sweetest person you'll ever meet. There are times I like to stick up for the little guy, and other times I want to squash 'em like a bug, and with each of the two options not caring about their cause.<br>
<br>
Alignment attempts to classify a person's behavior, but behavior can be so random that you can't classify it. I don't like the idea of killing mobs to make you seem good or evil. There's a big difference, in my opinion, between game mechanics and roleplaying. Roleplaying comes second to levelling up (As that is the point of the game, from my point of view), but in a close second. Just my two copper. <p>Vall Shadowstrife<BR>
Tier'Dal Scout of Luclin <BR>
Agent of The Ring <BR>
