 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/27/02 9:03:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1206.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Rules Change Proposal: Religious Conversion</span><hr size=1> First, I don't want this to become a thread trashing the alignment system.<br>
<br>
That said, I think there's a confusion about alignment among roleplayers in general.  One can be Good, and still a prick.  One can be nice, but Evil.  In fact, many interesting characters in literature are &quot;good&quot; jerks and sympathetic &quot;evil&quot; characters (in fact, John Milton's <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Paradise Lost</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> completely depends upon this: Satan is utterly sympathetic, and God comes off as a distant jerk).<br>
<br>
Second, I made the suggestion the way I did because it seems most consistent to the way the ruleset currently exists.  I really don't care how such a thing is implemented, although I think &quot;avowed worshipers&quot; of a particular deity (Clerics, Druids, Shaman, Druids, Paladins, ShadowKnights, and possibly Rangers and Beastlords) ought not have much, if any, latitude in changing deity.  As for all other classes, I think they ought to be allowed at least as much latitude as their race typically allows.<br>
<br>
In roleplay terms, shouldn't Gnome Clerics of Bertoxxulos (sp?) be out there trying to convert (pervert?) other Gnomes?  Wouldn't such issues get at the heart of some of the intraracial conflicts that are putatively going on on Norrath?<br>
<br>
